<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="93" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Lachemilla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lachemilla rothmaleriana" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rothmaleriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Lachemilla rothmaleriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. hispidula" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="hispidula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. hispidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. nivalis" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="nivalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. nivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its habit and erect stems with reduced leaves that fuse with the stipules to form verticillate sheaths, but differs by having trilobate lateral lobes. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. hispidula" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="hispidula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. hispidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an overall hispid pubescence, while 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. rothmaleriana" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rothmaleriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. rothmaleriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a characteristic sericeous-villous indumentum. Moreover, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. rothmaleriana" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rothmaleriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. rothmaleriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a turbinate-campanulate hypanthium with pilose-sericeous pubescence, while 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. hispidula" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="hispidula">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. hispidula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a globose-campanulate hypanthium with pilose-hirsute pubescence. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rothm" authorityYear="1937" baseAuthorityName="Kunth" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Lachemilla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Lachemilla nivalis" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nivalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">Lachemilla nivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a hypanthium with similar indumentum but its shape is only slightly campanulate. In the shape of sheath lobes, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. rothmaleriana" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="rothmaleriana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. rothmaleriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. galioides" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="galioides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="93">L. galioides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Benth.) Rothm., but the latter has slender stems, broader sheath lobes, and villous-hispid indumentum.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-Zenodo-Dep="3352511" doi="10.3897/phytokeys.127.36324.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/318147" pageId="0" pageNumber="93" start="Figure 5" startId="F5">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="93">
